    title: "Coastal Driving: How Salt Air and Sand Affect Your Tires",
    slug: "coastal-driving-salt-air-sand-tires",
    excerpt: "Living near the coast means your tires face unique challenges from salt air, sand, and wet roads. Learn how to protect your tires and choose the right ones.",
    content: `Coastal living comes with incredible perks: ocean views, beach access, and mild temperatures. But the coastal environment also presents unique challenges for your vehicle, especially your tires. Salt-laden air, sandy road surfaces, frequent fog, and perpetually damp conditions all affect tire performance and longevity in ways that inland drivers never experience. Here's what coastal drivers need to know.

Salt air accelerates the oxidation and degradation of rubber compounds. While tires are designed to resist environmental damage through UV inhibitors and anti-oxidants in the rubber, constant exposure to salt-heavy marine air breaks down these protective agents faster than normal. Coastal drivers often notice sidewall cracking and surface checking developing sooner than expected, sometimes within three to four years even on tires with plenty of remaining tread. Regular inspection of sidewalls and tire surfaces is essential. Rinsing your tires with fresh water during regular car washes helps remove salt deposits and slows degradation.

Sand is a hidden hazard for coastal drivers. Thin layers of sand blown across roads, especially near beaches, dunes, and coastal highways, dramatically reduce traction. Sand on pavement behaves like tiny ball bearings, eliminating the friction your tires rely on. This is especially dangerous on curves and during braking. Tires with strong wet-traction ratings tend to handle sandy surfaces better because the same siping and compound technology that grips wet roads also helps maintain contact on sandy pavement. Avoid hard braking or aggressive cornering where you see sand on the road.

Moisture is the constant companion of coastal driving. Morning fog, ocean mist, and frequent rain mean your tires spend more time on wet surfaces than the average driver's. Prioritize tires with excellent wet-weather performance ratings. The Continental CrossContact LX25, Michelin Defender LTX M/S 2, and Bridgestone Alenza AS Ultra are all top performers in wet conditions. For sedans and smaller vehicles, the Michelin Pilot Sport All Season 4 and Continental TrueContact Tour lead the wet-traction rankings. Even in mild coastal climates where snow is rare, the emphasis should always be on wet grip over cold-weather capability.

Coastal communities often have unique road surfaces. Salt spray accelerates pavement deterioration, so coastal roads may be rougher with more cracks and potholes than equivalent inland roads. Beach communities sometimes have unpaved or poorly maintained access roads. Tires with robust construction and sidewall protection handle these conditions with less risk of damage. When shopping on Ship.Tires for coastal driving, focus on wet performance, treadwear longevity, and compound durability. Spending a bit more on tires with superior rubber compounds will pay off in coastal environments where cheaper compounds degrade more rapidly. And remember to check your tires' DOT date codes annually since the coastal environment shortens the practical lifespan of any tire.`,
